  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT99-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">poruṇ muṟṟip pukunta talaimakaṉ “emmai niṉaittum aṟitirō” eṉṟa tōḻikkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by HIM, who entered having accumulated wealth, to the confidante who said “do you [still] know us, at least having thought [of us]?”.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT99">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                uḷḷiṉe ṉalleṉō yāṉē yuḷḷi</l>
<l>                niṉaittaṉe ṉalleṉō peritē niṉaittu</l>
<l>                maruṇṭaṉe ṉalleṉō vulakattup paṇpē</l>
<l>                nīṭiya maratta kōṭutōy malirniṟai</l>
<l>                yiṟaittuṇac ceṉṟaṟ ṟāaṅ</l>
<l>                kaṉaipperuṅ kāma mīṇṭukaṭaik koḷalē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <l>Didn't I remember [and], remembering,</l>
            <l>didn't I think a lot [of you/her?] [and], thinking [of you/her?]</l>
            <l>wasn't I confused about the state of the world:</l>
            <l rend="indent">that a desire so great would end here,</l>
            <l rend="indent">like the big flood that disperses,</l>
            <l rend="indent4">touching the long branches of trees,</l>
            <l rend="indent">[and then] subsides to be drunken<note place="foot">What is the exact syntax of <term xml:lang="ta">uṇa ceṉṟu aṟṟu</term>, where <term xml:lang="ta">ceṉṟu</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">aṟṟu</term> seem to express the same idea? And what is achieved with the image regarding the message of the whole? The wording seems to be a lament on the transitoriness of desire, but in the first three lines tradition understands, in accordance with the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term>, a solemn affirmation by the man that he has thought of HER when on his way, while the last line is read as desire satisfied in the moment of return ("while [now] such a big desire comes to an end ..."), and this is what agrees with the image: the flood does not disappear totally, but becomes useful by dwindling.</note>?</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
